'''John Joe Gray''' (born 15 March 1950) claims to be a [[Sovereign citizen movement|sovereign citizen]] and was a [[fugitive]] from the law. He currently lives on his 50-acre, wooded ranch in [[Trinidad, Texas]]. He was involved in the longest-running law enforcement standoff in American history, lasting a few days short of 15 years, before the district attorney dropped the charges.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernandez|first1=Manny |agency= |title=Lesson for Stalemated Sides in Oregon: A Texas Standoff Without End |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/08/us/lesson-for-stalemated-sides-in-oregon-a-texas-standoff-without-end.html |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=January 7, 2016 |accessdate=2016-01-07 }}</ref>
==Biography== The standoff began when Gray [[jump bail|jumped bail]] after being indicted on two counts of felony assault.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Nightline/john-joe-grays-militant-group-texas-compound/story?id=9819578 |title=John Joe Gray's Militant Group in Texas Compound |author=Terry Moran |publisher=ABC News |date=2010-02-12 |accessdate=2016-07-19}}</ref> During a traffic stop in [[Anderson County, Texas|Anderson County]], he allegedly attacked Texas Trooper Jim Cleland. A struggle ensued after Cleland reached for a .357 caliber handgun in the car in which Gray was in. Anti-government pamphlets and references to setting off a bomb on a highway overpass near Dallas were found in the vehicle. Gray was charged with two felonies, assault of a public servant and taking a police officer's weapon.<ref name="Houston Chronicle">{{cite news|author=Steve Campbell |url=http://www.chron.com/news/houston-texas/article/Authorities-ignore-fugitive-holed-up-on-Texas-1693380.php#photo-1217777 |title=Authorities ignore fugitive holed up on Texas land for 11 years - Houston Chronicle |publisher=Fort Worth Star-Telegram |date=2011-05-22 |accessdate=2016-07-19}}</ref> After promising to have no access to weapons while awaiting hearing, he was out on bail when the judge held his bond insufficient and ordered the re-arrest of John Joe Gray.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Kevin|title=Anti-government 'sovereign movement' on the rise in U.S.|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012-03-30/anti-government-militia-groups-freeman/53873496/1|accessdate=16 August 2016|publisher=USA Today|date=30 March 2012}}</ref>
Local [[Henderson County, Texas|Henderson County]] Sheriff Ray Nutt has stated "This kook is not worth it. Ten of him is not worth going up there and getting one of my young deputies killed."<ref name="Houston Chronicle" />
