{{Infobox scientist | honorific_prefix = | name = Ramiro Martinez Jr. | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1962}} | birth_place = [[San Antonio]], [[Texas]] | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = | period = | known_for = | title = | boards = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation--> | spouse = | children = | awards = <!--notable national level awards only--> | website = | education = | alma_mater = [[Ohio State University]] (Ph.D., 1992) | fields= [[Criminology]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | school_tradition = | doctoral_advisor = | influences = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | era = | workplaces = [[Northeastern University]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--only those with WP articles--> | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--must be referenced from a third party source--> | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | footnotes = }}
'''Ramiro Martinez Jr.''' (born 1962) is an American criminologist. He is a professor at [[Northeastern University]], in both the School of Criminology and Criminal Justice and the Department of Sociology and Anthropology.<ref name=ne>{{Cite web |url=https://www.northeastern.edu/cssh/faculty/ramiro-martinez |title=Ramiro Martinez, Jr. |website=Northeastern University}}</ref> He is also the chair of the [[American Sociological Association]]'s Section on Crime, Law, and Deviance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.asanet.org/communities/sections/sites/crime-law-and-deviance|title=Section on Crime, Law, and Deviance Information |website=Asanet.org |publisher=American Sociological Association}}</ref> He was born in [[San Antonio, Texas]], and taught at [[Florida International University]] before joining Northeastern. In 2006, while on sabbatical from Florida International University, he became a visiting scholar at the [[University of Houston]]'s Center for Mexican American Studies.<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Visiting Professor At UH Takes Aim At Houston Latinos And Crime |date=2006-09-25 |publisher=University of Houston |url=http://www.uh.edu/news-events/archive/nr/2006/09sept/092506_cmas_rmartinez.html}}</ref> His research focuses on variations in crime across ecological areas, and across racial and immigrant groups.<ref name=ne/> This research includes multiple studies showing that immigration from Mexico to the United States is associated with lower crime rates.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Baer |first=Drake |date=2016-08-03 |title=Immigration Is Probably the Best Way to Fight Crime |url=http://nymag.com/scienceofus/2016/08/immigration-is-probably-the-best-way-to-fight-crime.html |magazine=New York}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/03/08/173642807/does-crime-drop-when-immigrants-move-in |title=Does Crime Drop When Immigrants Move In? |last=Rose |first=Joel |website=NPR |publication-date=2013-03-08}}</ref>
